The paper proposes a theoretical framework for deep convolutional neural networks (DCNN) with ReLU nonlinearity. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the sub-category of Machine Learning (cs.LG) as it deals with the theoretical properties of deep neural networks. Additionally, the paper mentions regularization techniques such as Batch Norm, which is commonly used in neural networks and falls under the sub-category of Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE). The use of DCNN also suggests that the paper could belong to the sub-category of Computer Vision (cs.CV). The paper also mentions disentangled representations, which is a topic commonly studied in the sub-category of Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI). Finally, the paper's focus on understanding theoretical properties of deep networks suggests that it could also belong to the sub-category of Computation and Language (cs.CL), which deals with natural language processing and understanding.
